  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b9368599",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Interpreting the Random Forest Results\n",
    "The first full evaluation from previously gives a clear picture of how well the Random Forest model is learning from the engineered serve‑performance features. The results show a solid, well‑balanced model that performs consistently across both classes, with no major bias toward winners or losers.\n",
    "\n",
    "Performance overview\n",
    "- Accuracy: 0.793 - roughly 79% of match outcomes are predicted correctly.\n",
    "- Precision/Recall/F1 for both classes are tightly grouped around 0.78–0.82, indicating:\n",
    "- the model is not overfitting to one class,\n",
    "- both “win” and “loss” outcomes are being captured with similar reliability,\n",
    "- the engineered features are informative and stable.\n",
    "\n",
    "**What the confusion matrix reveals**\n",
    "\n",
    "[[1250  372]\n",
    "\n",
    " [ 300 1322]]\n",
    "\n",
    "This breakdown highlights two important patterns:\n",
    "- The model correctly identifies most winners (1322) and most losers (1250).\n",
    "- The error distribution is relatively symmetric:\n",
    "- 372 losers predicted as winners\n",
    "- 300 winners predicted as losers\n",
    "\n",
    "This symmetry is a good sign. It means the model is not simply “guessing winner” or “guessing loser” based on skewed patterns in the data.\n",
    "\n",
    "**What this tells us about the model**\n",
    "- The Random Forest is capturing meaningful relationships between serve efficiency and match outcomes.\n",
    "- The regularization choices (shallow trees, minimum leaf sizes, many estimators) are preventing overfitting.\n",
    "- The model is strong enough to serve as a baseline, but not so strong that it makes the other models unnecessary.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "7140f2d9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Grid Search for Random Forest Hyperparameters\n",
    "This next step introduces a systematic search for a better‑performing Random Forest configuration. Instead of relying on a single hand‑tuned model, the grid search evaluates multiple combinations of hyperparameters to identify the setup that maximizes predictive accuracy on the training folds. This approach is appropriate at this stage of the project because the baseline model already performs well, and the next logical step is to explore whether more optimized settings can extract additional signal from the serve‑performance features.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why this approach makes sense**\n",
    "- It explores tree depth, number of trees, minimum split/leaf sizes, and feature sampling strategies, all of which strongly influence Random Forest performance.\n",
    "- It uses 3‑fold cross‑validation, which balances computational cost with reliable estimates of generalization.\n",
    "- It evaluates accuracy, consistent with the earlier baseline evaluation.\n",
    "- It leverages parallel computation to speed up the search.\n",
    "\n",
    "**What the parameter grid covers**\n",
    "- n_estimators: 200 and 500 test whether more trees improve stability.\n",
    "- max_depth: 6, 8, 12 explore shallow to moderately deep trees.\n",
    "- min_samples_split: 2, 10, 20 test how aggressively trees are allowed to branch.\n",
    "- min_samples_leaf: 1, 5, 20 control leaf size and regularization strength.\n",
    "- max_features: 'sqrt' and 'log2' adjust feature subsampling to increase tree diversity.\n",
    "\n",
    "This grid is well‑designed: it is broad enough to explore meaningful model behavior but not so large that it becomes computationally excessive.\n"
   ]
  },
