    "### Interpreting the Examples\n",
    "**The correctly** predicted matches typically show clear statistical patterns: the winning player often has higher first‑serve points won, stronger second‑serve performance, and better overall serve efficiency. These are the features the model consistently ranks as most important, and they align with tennis fundamentals: holding serve reliably is one of the strongest predictors of match success.\n",
    "\n",
    "Why the model got it right:\n",
    "- Player A had a significantly higher first‑serve points won percentage (e.g., 74% vs. 58%).\n",
    "- Player A also held a strong second‑serve performance, which the model heavily weights.\n",
    "- Combined, these stats indicate Player A was consistently winning free points and protecting their service games.\n",
    "- The model recognizes this pattern as highly predictive of match success, especially in ATP/WTA‑level play where holding serve is critical.\n",
    "\n",
    "This kind of example shows the model is correctly capturing the statistical backbone of modern tennis: efficient serving correlates strongly with winning.\n",
    "\n",
    "**The incorrect** predictions reveal the model’s limitations. In some matches, a player may have strong serve percentages but still lose due to factors not captured in the dataset, such as poor serve placement, weak rally tolerance, tactical errors, or physical issues. Tennis is a sport where a high first‑serve percentage does not guarantee dominance if the serve lacks depth or variation. These examples highlight that while the model captures broad statistical trends, it cannot account for qualitative aspects of performance.\n",
    "\n",
    "Why the model got it wrong:\n",
    "- Player C may have had a high first‑serve percentage, but the model cannot see serve quality—placement, depth, spin, or predictability.\n",
    "- Player D may have been a strong returner, neutralizing Player C’s serve despite the high percentage.\n",
    "- The model also cannot capture momentum swings, mental lapses, or injury‑related dips that occur mid‑match.\n",
    "- In tennis, a high first‑serve percentage can be misleading if the serve lacks pace or tactical variation.\n",
    "- This is a classic case where raw efficiency stats don’t tell the full story.\n",
    "\n",
    "These examples help stakeholders understand that the model is not “wrong” so much as it is limited by the available features (just like any statistical model in sports)."
   ]
