    "## Conclusion\n",
    "The project successfully demonstrated that match outcomes in professional tennis can be predicted with solid accuracy using serve‑performance statistics. Across three different supervised learning models (Random Forest, Logistic Regression, and Gradient Boosting) the results were consistent, stable, and aligned with tennis fundamentals. The engineered serve‑efficiency features proved highly predictive, and the models showed balanced behavior across classes, confirming the reliability of the dataset and preprocessing pipeline. The interpretability analysis further highlighted that first‑serve points won, second‑serve points won, and overall serve efficiency are the dominant drivers of match outcomes, which matches domain knowledge from competitive tennis.\n",
    "\n",
    "Real match examples illustrated how the model’s predictions reflect meaningful tennis patterns. Correct predictions typically involved players with strong serve efficiency and consistent point‑winning ability, while incorrect predictions often stemmed from factors not captured in the dataset, such as serve placement, tactical decisions, physical condition, or momentum shifts. These examples highlight both the strengths of the model and the inherent complexity of tennis performance.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Limitations\n",
    "Several limitations should be acknowledged to contextualize the results:\n",
    "- Feature scope: The dataset focuses primarily on serve‑related statistics. Tennis outcomes depend on many additional factors: return quality, rally tolerance, movement, tactical patterns, and mental resilience, that are not represented in the current features.\n",
    "- Data granularity: Match‑level aggregates hide important within‑match dynamics such as momentum swings, pressure points, or set‑by‑set performance changes.\n",
    "- Model assumptions: Logistic Regression assumes linear relationships; tree‑based models assume that splits capture the relevant interactions. Neither approach can fully capture tactical nuance or qualitative aspects of play.\n",
    "- Unobserved variables: Injury, fatigue, surface preference, weather conditions, and head‑to‑head history are not included but can significantly influence outcomes.\n",
    "- Serve quality vs. serve percentage: High first‑serve percentage does not always translate to effectiveness if the serve lacks pace or placement. The model cannot distinguish between “good” and “neutralized” serves.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Future Work\n",
    "Several improvements could enhance predictive performance and deepen the analysis:\n",
    "- Expand the feature set by incorporating return statistics, rally metrics, break‑point performance, and surface‑specific indicators.\n",
    "- Integrate contextual variables such as player rankings, head‑to‑head history, fatigue indicators (e.g., match duration the day before), and tournament level.\n",
    "- Add temporal structure by modeling set‑level or game‑level data, which would capture momentum and pressure situations more accurately.\n",
    "- Address qualitative aspects by incorporating tracking data (serve placement, ball speed, shot patterns) where available.\n",
    "- Experiment with advanced models such as XGBoost, LightGBM, or neural networks to capture more complex interactions.\n",
    "- Perform calibration analysis to evaluate how well predicted probabilities reflect true win likelihoods.\n",
    "- Expand the dataset with more seasons or additional tours (WTA, Challenger) to improve generalization.\n"
